The paper deals with the problem of recovering sparse signals from linear measurements, which is a fundamental problem in information theory (cs.IT), data structures (cs.DS), machine learning (cs.LG), distributed computing (cs.DC), and computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper investigates the recoverability of sparse signals under integrality constraints, which is a novel and important direction in compressed sensing and optimization. The paper also discusses the computational complexity of the recovery problem and presents some numerical experiments, which are relevant to both theoretical computer science and practical applications. Overall, the paper covers a broad range of topics in computer science and is likely to be of interest to researchers in multiple sub-fields.
